<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-02-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-02-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="551" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d551">
                        <head>No. 551.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">L. S.
                                    Sackville West</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Bayard</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-02-05"><hi rend="italic">February</hi> 5,
                                1888</date>. (Received February 7.)</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the case of certain
                            American vessels in distress at Halifax I have the honor to inform you
                            that the Marquis of <pb facs="0916" n="780" xml:id="pg_780"/> Salisbury
                            has telegraphed to me to the effect that permission has been granted to
                            land part of their perishable cargo in order to operate <hi rend="italic">bona fide</hi> repairs, but without prejudice to the
                            question of right.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">L. S. Sackville
                                    West.</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>